Wyclif, by the force of his definition, goes a great deal farther than Aquinas or than the Decretals; yet he quotes them all along as if they applied to simony understood in his sense, not in theirs. As his definition overlaps the other, it very frequently happens that his application is right, but not always. By the by, it is curious to note with what evident respect he sets aside the opinion of that Holy Doctor (a sancto doctore, p. 14).
